We let the vector $\mathbf{v}$ be the velocity vector. If the bee
travels along a path in $\mathbb{R}^{3}$ given by
$[x(t),y(t),z(t)]^{T}$, then $\mathbf{v}$ is given by

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{d}{dt}x(t), \frac{d}{dt}y(t), \frac{d}{dt}z(t) \end{bmatrix}^{T}
\end{align*}
We are told that the bee is travelling along a path defined by the
intersection of the two surfaces\begin{align*}
3z + x^{2} + y^{2} = 2
\end{align*} and
$z = x^{2} - y^{2}$. Therefore, we can differentiate each relationship
with respect to t to get a pair of equations describing the velocity of
the bee at any point along the curve:

\begin{align*}
3\frac{dz}{dt} + 2x\frac{dx}{dt} + 2y\frac{dy}{dt} = 0, \quad \frac{dz}{dt} = 2x\frac{dx}{dt} - 2y\frac{dy}{dt}.
\end{align*}
We are interested in analyzing the velocity at (1,1,0), so plug this
point into the above equations:

\begin{align*}
3\frac{dz}{dt} + 2\frac{dx}{dt} + 2\frac{dy}{dt} = 0, \quad \frac{dz}{dt} - 2\frac{dx}{dt} + 2\frac{dy}{dt} = 0.
\end{align*}
Solving the two equations to get $\frac{dx}{dt},\,\frac{dy}{dt}$ in
terms of $\frac{dz}{dt}$ gives:

\begin{align*}
\frac{dx}{dt} = -\frac{1}{2}\frac{dz}{dt}, \quad \frac{dy}{dt} = -\frac{dz}{dt}
\end{align*}
So at the point (1,1,0), we can write the velocity vector in terms of
$z'(t)$:

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} = \left(\frac{d}{dt}z(t)\right)\begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{2}, -1, 1 \end{bmatrix}^{T}.
\end{align*}
We know that the speed of the bee is 6 at the point (1,1,0), so we use
the equation

\begin{align*}
|\mathbf{v}| =\left(\sqrt{\left(\frac{d}{dt}z(t)\right)^{2}}\right)\left(\sqrt{\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2} + \left(-1\right)^{2} + \left(1\right)^{2}}\right) = 6
\end{align*}
Solving for $\frac{dz}{dt}$ gives

\begin{align*}
\left(\sqrt{\left(\frac{d}{dt}z(t)\right)^{2}}\right) = \frac{6}{\sqrt{9/4}} = 4 \quad \rightarrow \quad \frac{d}{dt}z(t) = \pm 4.
\end{align*}
Taking the positive solution, (since the bee is travelling in the
direction of increasing z, we can write the velocity vector

\begin{align*}
{\color{blue}\mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} -2, -4, 4 \end{bmatrix}^{T}}
\end{align*}
